urnaround for the worldwide mining company.   If approved by shareholders, the deal announced Wednesday willexpand Amax's mining operations and mark its return to nickelproduction. Toronto-based Falconbridge is the world'ssecond-largest nickel producer.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sales of new homes climbed 5.5 percent inJune, the government said, in a report that gave some economistshope that a rebound in housing will help keep the country out of arecession this year.   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that sales of newsingle-family homes rose to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of670,000 units in June as sales continued to respond favorably tofalling mortgage rates after skidding in March to their slowestpace in more than six years.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Orders for manufactured goods edged up aslight 0.4 percent in June, reflecting a rebound in demand formilitary hardware, the government reported.   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that new orders formanufactured goods totaled a seasonally adjusted $234.6 billion inJune following a 2.6 percent plunge in May.</TEXT><DATELINE>CLEARWATER, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A jury rejected Home Shopping Network's$1.5 billion lawsuit charging GTE Corp. with providing faultytelephone equipment and instead awarded $100 million to two GTEsubsidiaries for libel and slander.   The cable television retailer claimed it lost millions of callsand $500 million in potential sales in 1986 and early 1987 becauseGTE telephone equipment it contracted for could not handle thevolume of calls.   But on Wednesday, a Pinellas County Court jury rejected chargesof fraud, negligent misrepresentation, breach of trust andconfidence, and breach of fiduciary duty against thetelecommunications giant.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The House voted tentatively to make thesmoking ban on most airline flights permanent, but decided not toconsider extending the prohibition to all routes.   On a 259-169 vote Wednesday, lawmakers adopted language thatwould make permanent the current ban on smoking on flights of twohours or less, which otherwise will expire next April.   But the provision forbade consideration of a proposal to extendthe ban to all domestic flights.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal regulators have allowed the nation'seighth-largest savings and loan to become a commercial bank,potentially reducing revenue to the beleaguered fund insuring Sandamp;Ldeposits by millions of dollars.   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, in a decision late Tuesday,said Home Federal Savings and Loan Association of San Diego couldleave the insolvent Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market turned upward Wednesday, as the Dow Jonesaverage of 30 industrials climbed 16.32 points to 2,657.44.   The dollar gained against most major foreign currencies in U.S.dealings after weakening abroad.   Bond prices edged lower.   Cocoa futures prices surged; sugar continued rallying; soybeansfell to a new low for the seventh time in eight days; livestock andpork futures were sharply higher; and petroleum futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>